'''Tenman-sha''' (てんまんしゃ) is a shrine in {{ill|lt=Hachiōji|Q208863|WD=Q208863|1=Hachiōji}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Tokyo|1=UNKNOWN}}. It is the origin of the place name {{ill|lt=Kitano-chō (Hachiōji)|Q11404303|WD=Q11404303|lt=Kitano-chō|1=Kitanomachi}}. Its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}; this article also explains the subordinate {{ill|lt=Shiogama Shrine|Q133753|WD=Q133753|lt=Shiogama Shrine|1=Shiogama shrine}}.

=== History ===
* The founding is unknown; it is said a branch of the {{ill|lt=Yokoyama-tō|Q11542517|WD=Q11542517|1=Yokoyama-tō}} invited {{ill|lt=Kitano Tenmangū|Q662176|WD=Q662176|lt=Kyoto Kitano Tenmangū|1=Kitano Tenmangū}} here<ref>'Hachiōji Naganuma-chō, Kitano-chō Wagamachi,' Masayuki Shimizu, Onkodō, 1987.</ref><ref>'Hachiōji Jiten,' Hachiōji Jiten no Kai, Katakura Shoten, 2001.</ref>.
* From {{ill|lt=1591|Q6766|WD=Q6766|1=1591}} ({{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 19) to {{ill|lt=1860|Q7691|WD=Q7691|1=1860}} ({{ill|lt=Man'en|Q1193862|WD=Q1193862|1=Man'en}} 1), it received 5 koku of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=sharyō|1=UNKNOWN}} land{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}.
* In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, prayer talismans for the shogun's military fortune were offered every year{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}.
* In the {{ill|lt=1600s|Q42995|WD=Q42995|1=1600s (decade)}}, the sacred {{ill|lt=zelkova|Q920344|WD=Q920344|1=Zelkova serrata}} tree was planted.
* In {{ill|lt=1664|Q7581|WD=Q7581|1=1664}} ({{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|WD=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 4), shrine buildings were rebuilt.
* In {{ill|lt=1880|Q7806|WD=Q7806|1=1880}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 13), the shrine building with {{ill|lt=karahafu|Q977293|WD=Q977293|1=Karahafu}}-fronted portico was rebuilt.
* In {{ill|lt=1963|Q2755|WD=Q2755|1=1963}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 38), during land readjustment around {{ill|lt=Kitano Station (Tokyo)|Q4222444|WD=Q4222444|lt=Kitano Station|1=Kitano Station (Tokyo)}}, the Kitano Stone Age dwelling site (city-designated cultural property), formerly on grounds of {{ill|lt=Hachiōji Municipal Yui Daiichi Elementary School|Q11391597|WD=Q11391597|lt=Yui Daiichi Elementary School|1=Yui Daiichi Elementary School}}, was relocated{{sfn|八王子市}}.
* In {{ill|lt=1976|Q2480|WD=Q2480|1=1976}} (Shōwa 51), for the 1075th memorial of Kankō (Michizane), the shrine roof was renovated with copper sheeting.

=== Sacred tree ===
The zelkova said to have been planted in the {{ill|lt=1600s|Q42995|WD=Q42995|1=1600s (decade)}} still stands in the precincts.

Since the 2010s, branches of zelkova and cherry trees around the shrine perimeter extended over roads, and the city repeatedly gave {{ill|lt=administrative guidance|Q4683583|WD=Q4683583|1=Administrative guidance}} to prune them. In December 2019, the {{ill|lt=Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism|Q1376196|WD=Q1376196|1=Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism}} also instructed pruning within that month, but there were no signs of compliance<ref>[https://www.asahi.com/articles/ASM9N3TFVM9NUTIL010.html?iref=com_rnavi_arank_nd04 Dangerous "sacred tree" even hides traffic lights: shrine's explanation for not removing it] - {{ill|lt=Asahi Shimbun|Q720503|WD=Q720503|1=The Asahi Shimbun}}</ref>. On June 20, 2020, the MLIT Sōbu National Highway Office and Hachiōji City, under the Administrative Execution Act, forcibly cut protruding branches<ref>{{Citenews|title=Hachiōji City and the state conduct administrative execution to cut sacred tree: branches/leaves over roads, shrine ignored 22 rounds of guidance|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20200621/k00/00m/040/020000c|newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun|date=2020-06-21|accessdate=2020-06-21}}</ref>.

=== Cultural property ===
; Kitano Stone Age dwelling site: Hachiōji city-designated historic site / old site{{sfn|八王子市}}

=== Transport ===
* 3 minutes on foot from north exit of {{ill|lt=Kitano Station (Tokyo)|Q4222444|WD=Q4222444|lt=Kitano Station|1=Kitano Station (Tokyo)}} on the {{ill|lt=Keiō Line|Q1323112|WD=Q1323112|1=Keiō Line}}{{sfn|東京都神社庁}}
* {{ill|lt=Hachiōji Bypass|Q11391552|WD=Q11391552|1=Hachioji bypass}} {{ill|lt=Uchikoshi Interchange|Q11497261|WD=Q11497261|lt=Uchikoshi IC|1=Uchikoshi IC}}

=== Shiogama Shrine ===
Also called {{ill|lt=Shiogama Shrine|Q133753|WD=Q133753|1=Shiogama shrine}}. It is famous as a shrine for abdominal-belt prayers for safe childbirth. It stands to the right of Tenman-sha.
